text:
Madison Avenue, S.W. corner of 27th Street, showing New York Jockey Club House, demolished before 1910.
The view is west on 27th Street. The arch shown at the left of the picture is part of Madison Square Garden (1890-1925). The small buildings on 27th Street between the Jockey Club and the newly erected Brunswick Building are old stables; in a few more years they will begin giving way to office buildings.
Probably about 1907.

Brown Brothers, Photographers.

Madison Avenue, west side, between 27th and 28th Streets, showing new office buildings Nos. 72-76. The two story Mott Memorial Library, shown in part on the left, and the Columbus Apartments Hotel, the building with fire escapes, will be demolished between 1915-18 to build Madison Avenue wing of Prince George Hotel. 1911.

Madison Avenue, west side, from 27th to 28th Streets, showing the Mott Memorial Library, a free medical library, at 64 Madison Avenue (the 3-story building). The building on the northwest corner of 27th Street is the Hotel Madison. Next come the Mott Memorial and the Columbus Apartments, both of which will be demolished about 1917 to make room for a wing of the Prince George Hotel. Above them are shown 72-76 Madison Avenue, two newly built office buildings.

1911.

East 27th Street, adjoining and east of the N.E. corner of Madison Ave. In the foreground, in silhouette are several of the pillars of the old Madison Square Garden.

About 1920.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.

Madison Avenue, east side, at E. 27th Street, showing un- known (to the writer) individuals leaving the old Madison Square Garden (right). The photographer is viewing northeastward to show at the left buildings on the north side of E. 27th Street to the east of Madison Avenue.

prior to 1923.

63-71 Madison Avenue, east side, from 27th Street about halfway to 28th Street, showing a new office building 65-7 Madison Avenue, nearing completion. It replaces two small houses. Notice that Madison Avenue is temporarily a one-way street. 1923.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.
Madison Avenue, east side, between 27th and 28th Streets, a new building, replacing two small structures. 1923.

Madison Ave., east side, south from and including East 27th Street. The view shows the old Madison Square Garden, with the Yiddish Art Theatre occupying the N.W. corner. August 13, 1924.

Eugene L, Armbruster, Collection.
